<article>
    <h1>TRAIN LIKE A THAI BOXER</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201222/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-22"><time>2020-12-22</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | TRAVEL</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Get your blood pump­ing while ex­pe­ri­enc­ing Thai cul­ture by sign­ing up for a Muay Thai, or Thai box­ing, class.</p>
    <p>The mar­tial art is the na­tional sport of Thai­land and was prac­tised by the sol­diers of for­mer King Nare­suan, who ruled Siam – Thai­land’s for­mer name – around the 16th cen­tury.</p>
    <p>Thanks to movies such as Ong-Bak: Muay Thai War­rior (2003) and Beau­ti­ful Boxer (2003), the sport ex­pe­ri­enced a burst of pop­u­lar­ity in the 2000s and still at­tracts be­gin­ners to­day.</p>
    <p>The Chowraiooi Muay Thai gym at Golden Mile Com­plex of­fers pay-as-you-come ses­sions at $40 each, as well as other pack­ages and plans.</p>
    <p>Af­fil­i­ated with the Chowraiooi Box­ing Gym in Thai­land, it is led by head trainer Robert Yap, 42, the team man­ager of Sin­ga­pore’s na­tional Muay Thai team, as well as a mas­ter trainer at the Sin­ga­pore Muaythai Fed­er­a­tion.</p>
    <p>Dur­ing the ses­sions, you will learn ba­sic stances, as well as pad work, shadow box­ing and cir­cuit-based bag work – enough to work up a sweat. When you are ready, you can progress to the gym’s large spar­ring ring.</p>
    <p>Although Muay Thai is a com­bat sport, the at­mos­phere at the gym is con­vivial, and all Mr Yap asks is that be­gin­ners come rar­ing to ex­er­cise and prefer­ably with a sense of hu­mour.</p>

